# ── Internal development docs (kept on disk, out of the public repo) ─────────
# These are development/process/governance docs and the AI-agent bootstrap. They
# are intentionally NOT published so the public repo stays consumer-focused. They
# remain in the working tree for local reference. Consumer-relevant docs (README,
# CHANGELOG, compatibility-matrix, diagnostics-codes, authoring guide, SECURITY,
# clean-room-policy, deployment, docs-site) stay tracked.
CLAUDE.md
PROGRESS.md
DEV-NOTES.local.md
CHANGELOG.dev.local.md
docs/progress-archive.md
docs/coding-standards.md
docs/pdf-spec-notes.md
docs/secrets-and-credentials.md
docs/accessibility.md
docs/RELEASE.md
docs/phases/
docs/design/
docs/legal/
docs/security/security-hardening-plan.md
docs/security/fuzzing.md
.claude/skills/

# macOS Finder / iCloud / Time Machine duplicate files (e.g., `Foo 2.cs`).
# Scoped to source-shaped extensions only — these are the file types where
# a duplicate produces real build damage (CS source: duplicate-type defs;
# MSBuild config: redefined targets; properties.json duplicate: source-gen
# crash). Per Task 18 hardening 2 review Rec 4, the patterns intentionally
# do NOT match .html / .txt / .md / .png / .pdf / etc. so legitimate
# numbered docs, fixtures, and assets (`Sample 2.html`, `screenshot 3.png`)
# are tracked normally. Directory.Build.props provides the matching
# compile-time defense for `.cs` only. Force-add a legitimately named
# numbered file with `git add -f path/to/file`.
#
# Two glob shapes paired to cover single-digit and two-digit suffixes
# (`Foo 0.cs` .. `Foo 99.cs`) — Copilot review on PR #12 caught that
# the previous `1[0-9]` pattern missed `Foo 20.cs` and beyond.
* [0-9].cs
* [1-9][0-9].cs
* [0-9].csproj
* [1-9][0-9].csproj
* [0-9].props
* [1-9][0-9].props
* [0-9].targets
* [1-9][0-9].targets
* [0-9].json
* [1-9][0-9].json

# Finder-style "Foo 2.cs" duplicates from macOS dup-on-copy / Time Machine restore.
# Aligns with Directory.Build.props DefaultItemExcludes.
* [2-9].cs
* [1-9][0-9].cs

# Finder-duplicate hygiene for the public/orphan-branch launch (RC-3 / WP-8).
# The extensions below are generated docs (docfx `.yml`/`.manifest`), CI/config
# (`.yml`/`.yaml`), and prose docs (`.md`) that live in *tracked* directories
# (.github/workflows, docs-site/api, docs/security, …). A `Foo 2.md` there is
# never legitimate — it's a Time Machine / iCloud dup — and an orphan-branch
# bulk `git add` would otherwise sweep it (incl. duplicate live workflow files)
# into the first public commit. No legitimately-numbered file of these types is
# tracked; force-add one with `git add -f` if that ever changes. Unlike the
# source-shaped patterns above this intentionally also covers `.md` because the
# launch-hygiene risk (dups of consumer docs like deployment.md) outweighs the
# `.html`/`.png` fixture concern that kept `.md` out of the source list.
* [0-9].yml
* [1-9][0-9].yml
* [0-9].yaml
* [1-9][0-9].yaml
* [0-9].manifest
* [1-9][0-9].manifest
* [0-9].md
* [1-9][0-9].md
